(Beginner) Quest 5: AvalancheJS
Introduction
Previously in Quests 3 and 4, we learnt how AvalancheGo APIs can be used to interact with the 3 built-in blockchains of Avalanche. In this quest, we’ll be learning about AvalancheJS, a JavaScript library that provides similar functionalities to AvalancheGo.
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe AvalancheJS and its uses
  • Use AvalancheJS to interact with the X-Chain
  • Create a keypair on the X-Chain
  • Create and send an asset on the X-Chain
  • Transfer AVAX tokens from one built-in blockchain to another
Deliverable
This quest has one deliverable.
  1. A screenshot of your Avalanche Wallet and terminal output. Follow instructions in Step 12 for more details.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to AvalancheJS
AvalancheJS is a JavaScript Library used for interacting with the Avalanche platform. It is built using TypeScript and intended to support both the browser and Node.js. Similar to the AvalancheGo APIs, the AvalancheJS library allows one to issue commands to the Avalanche node APIs.
These are some of the functionalities that are available with AvalancheJs:
  • Locally manage private keys
  • Retrieve balances on addresses
  • Issue signed transactions to the X-Chain, P-Chain and C-Chain on the Primary network
  • Create a Subnetwork
  • Swap AVAX and assets between the X-Chain, P-Chain and C-Chain

More information regarding AvalancheJS can be found here.
Step 2: Situations to Use AvalancheJS
So, when do we use AvalancheJS? The APIs supported by AvalancheJS allow any Javascript/Typescript developer to interact with a node on Avalanche. The APIs supported by AvalancheJS library allow for interaction with the P-Chain, X-Chain and C-Chain.  
With this library, developers will be able to manage their own private keys, retrieve balances from their wallet addresses, retrieve Avalanche network information from a node and issue signed transactions to the P-Chain, X-Chain and C-Chain on the Avalanche network.

Although AvalancheJS is a powerful tool, it is not used in situations when you want to interact with the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) on the C-Chain. For example, when you’re issuing transactions or writing functions to interact with deployed smart contracts on the C-Chain. 

For these situations, using libraries that are specifically built for EVM interaction such as web3.js or ethers.js are more appropriate. In fact, we’ll be using ethers.js in the later portions of this campaign (Quests 9 and 11), so stay tuned!
Step 3: Requirements
AvalancheJS requires Node.js version 14.18.0 or higher to compile. Make sure both Node and NPM are installed. To check you have Node.js installed, open a terminal and run the following command. 
node -v

If it is already installed, a version number should be returned. Remember to ensure that the version returned is higher than 14.18.0. If your version of Node.js is lower than that, refer here for a guide on how to update your Node.js version.

To check if you have npm installed, run the following command. Similarly, a version number should be returned.

npm -v

Next, you’ll also need to have Git installed on your machine to download the Typescript files. You can check if git is installed by using the following command. This command would return you the git version if git has been installed. If you don’t have git installed, you can refer to the following guides for how to install git to your machine:
  • Windows guide
  • Mac guide

git --version

Lastly, you’ll need a code/text editor of your choice. You are free to use any code editor of your choice, but our recommendation is Visual Studio Code.
Step 4: Overview of Quest
Alright, now our local set up is done and we’re ready to start proper with the quest!
Let’s first start off with an overview of the subsequent steps. We’ll begin by cloning a project repository from Github. This project repository contains some AvalancheJS functions that will be used to create a wallet, create an asset and transfer that asset to another wallet. 

Along the way, we’ll also fund the wallet with some Testnet AVAX tokens. Then, we'll swap tokens from the C-Chain to the X-Chain. 

Ready? Let’s go!
Step 5: Cloning the Project
As mentioned, let’s start off first by cloning the project folder from the git repository. Essentially, cloning in git creates a local copy of the repository on your local machine. To start, open your terminal and navigate the directory to your desired location and run the following commands, starting with the one below. 
git clone -b avax-quest-5 https://github.com/stackup-dev/advancing-into-avalanche.git

Once you run the command above, you will see a folder with the name “advancing-into-avalanche”. Now you will need to change the directory of your terminal to enter the new folder, you can do this using the command below.

cd advancing-into-avalanche

Now that you are inside the project directory, you will need to install the necessary libraries to run the code. You can run the command below to install the libraries that are configured in the package.json file. This will also include the AvalancheJS library. 

npm install

Once that is done, you can start running the code using the command below.

npm run start
 

The first message you should see on your terminal is “Please change the step variable to either 6, 10 or 11!”. This means that the script is running properly. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you require a reference.

Step 6: Creating the Keypair
In the src folder, open up the index.ts file in your code editor. We will be looking at the code here for the next few steps. Don’t worry if the script seems overwhelming, we’ll be tackling the important chunks of code one by one!
We highly recommend turning off the “Auto Save” feature of your code editor for this quest as it will make following along a lot clearer. The code is designed in such a way that once it starts, it will continuously monitor the script for any changes and run the code again when a change is saved. As such, your terminal output might start to become cluttered if “Auto Save” is not turned off.



Since we’ll be connecting to the Avalanche Fuji Testnet, the configurations are edited accordingly, as seen in the image above.



Before we can understand the chunk of code above, we’ll need to first understand the concept of keychains and keypairs. AvalancheJS comes with its own AVM Keychain - this keychain is used in the functions of the API, enabling them to sign using keys it has registered. In line 54, the keychain is accessed through the X-Chain and referenced through the variable keychain.

The keychain has the ability to create new keypairs for you. If keypair is an unfamiliar term to you, pause and take a guess as to what it is… A keypair is, well, a pair of keys! Not just any pair of keys, it’s a pair of private and public keys. Sounds familiar? What we’re doing here is essentially creating a wallet! In line 56, we make this new wallet and reference it with the variable keypair.

In this keypair object, we have the ability to extract useful information such as its address, private key and public key, alongside other pieces of information. This can be seen from lines 58 to 60.



Since we want to get 2 wallets, 1 for creating and sending the asset and 1 for receiving the asset, we’ll need to generate 2 keypairs. This can be seen from line 64 to 68, where we’re essentially repeating the same process 1 more time using the same keychain object.

Alright, time to see the code in action! In line 32, change the value of step from 0 to 6. After you make the change, save your script. After saving, open up your terminal again and you should see that 2 sets of keypair information are now showing as output in your terminal, similar to the image below. Do note that keypairs are randomly generated, therefore the the values of the address, publicKey and privateKey you see in the image below will not match the output you see in your terminal.



Now we’ll need to copy and paste the information from our terminal into our script. Replace the string values in lines 25 to 30 accordingly. Leave assetId as it is for now. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you require a reference.﻿

Step 7: Importing Keypair to Avalanche Wallet
As we mentioned in the previous steps, we will need to add AVAX Testnet tokens to our sender’s wallet. The reason why we need to do this is because transactions on most blockchains, including Avalanche, require gas fees (as explained in earlier quests). 
Also note that as we are executing this transaction on the X-Chain, these gas fees would have to be paid in AVAX. Recall that we covered this in Quest 2 where we compared the C-Chain to Subnets. For this portion of the quest, we’ll be using a new wallet interface - Avalanche Wallet. 

The reason why we’re using Avalanche Wallet is because it allows us to transfer AVAX tokens from 1 built-in blockchain to another. The concept to takeaway here is that each built-in blockchain on Avalanche’s Primary Network uses its own native AVAX tokens. In other words, you can’t use C-Chain’s AVAX tokens to pay for transactions on the X-Chain. You would first need to convert your AVAX tokens from the C-Chain to the X-Chain.

The faucet that we’ll be using only dispenses AVAX tokens on the C-Chain, therefore we’ll need to have a means to convert our AVAX tokens on the C-Chain to the X-Chain since our asset will be created on the X-Chain. Avalanche Wallet provides a really convenient way of doing so.

First, let’s head to Avalanche Wallet, which is a web page you can use to interface with your wallets, among other services. Once you reach the site, make sure that your network on the top right-hand corner of your screen is toggled to Fuji instead of Mainnet. 

Once you have confirmed that you are on the Fuji testnet, click on ‘ACCESS WALLET’. On the next page, select the first option, i.e. ‘Private Key’. Once you have selected it, you’ll be prompted to enter your private key. In this case, copy the sender’s private key from your terminal and paste it into the textbox. Once that is successful, it will bring you to the homepage of your wallet, similar to the image in ‘Expected output’.
Expected output
Step 8: Getting AVAX Tokens from Faucet

You will need to ensure that the X-Chain address tallies with your sender keypair’s address. Once you confirm that the addresses tally, click on the area indicated in the image above to get the C-Chain address and copy it. 

Next, head to the Avalanche Faucet site.



The first thing that you will need to do on the faucet site is to ensure that the network selected is Fuji (C-Chain). Then, you will need to paste your C-Chain wallet address into the textbox indicated in the image above. Once that is done, you can click on the ‘REQUEST 2 AVAX’ button.

Troubleshooting: if you have already submitted a request to the faucet in the past 24 hours and intend to make another request, you’ll notice that you’ll be faced with a 24 hour cooldown. Please try to identify the wallet that contains the previously located testnet tokens and transfer your tokens from that wallet instead. 

However, if you have lost access to that wallet and are still facing the cooldown blocker, you can request for Fuji AVAX testnet tokens from Avalanche’s Developer Relations team in their Discord server’s developers-chat. Note that this should not be your first option - be prudent with your testnet tokens.
Step 9: Swapping AVAX Tokens From C-Chain to X-Chain
How to start
Once the transaction is successful, you can return to the Avalanche Wallet and you should see that your wallet now has 2 AVAX tokens on the C-Chain. If you don’t see your balance reflecting the change, you might need to press on the refresh icon beside ‘Balance’ to do so. Refer to the image in ‘How to start’ for a reference.  
As explained earlier, each of the built-in blockchains in the Primary Network have their own AVAX token and they cannot be used to pay for transactions on the other blockchains. Hence the need to convert our C-Chain AVAX tokens to X-Chain AVAX tokens as that is where our asset will be created. 



To convert the tokens, you will need to click on the ‘Cross Chain’ option on the left side bar. After that, you’ll need to ensure that your ‘Source Chain’ is set to C Chain while your 
‘Destination Chain’ is set to X Chain. After you have set the Source and Destination Chains, you will need to set the amount. 

We’ll be transfering the maximum number of available AVAX tokens to the X-Chain. You can do so by clicking the ‘MAX’ button under ‘Transfer Amount’. Once that is done, click on the ‘CONFIRM’ button. The button will then change to a ‘TRANSFER’ button in the same place, so we’ll need to click on that again.
 
Once the transaction is confirmed, look at the ‘Balance’ section of the page and you’ll see that your tokens are now on the X-Chain! Now that our sender’s wallet is loaded up with AVAX tokens on the X-Chain, we can move on to the next steps of creating the asset.
Step 10: Creating the Asset
Now let’s head back to index.ts to cover the code that’s used for creating the asset. In particular, we’re referring to the createAsset() function, which spans from line 76 to 132.


The first part involves importing your keypair using the private key provided and then from there, extracting out the address that will be used to pay for the gas fee.



The next portion involves preparing the mint output. The outputs array will hold the result of the minting process. threshold is the number of signers required to sign the transaction - for this quest we will be using just 1 signer. locktime refers to the amount of seconds that the output can be spent after, here we define it to be 0. memo represents the text we would want to add to the transaction. 



The next part is providing the basic information for your asset that you want to create. Here, change the value of name to your StackUp username and the value of symbol to SU. denomination refers to the smallest possible unit of transfer of this token. Here we give it the value of 3, meaning that the smallest possible amount that we can transfer is 0.001 of a token.



The next part involves getting the UTXO. The X-Chain stores all available balances in a datastore called Unspent Transaction Outputs (UTXOs). A UTXO set is the unique list of outputs produced by transactions, addresses that can spend the amount in the output, and other variables such as lockout times and thresholds. All these have already been set in lines 83 to 88 earlier on.



After this, we will need to create the initial state of the asset. To do that, we will need to define a few things. Firstly, we set the initial amount of asset tokens created to be 1000. Then we define the addresses to charge the gas fees to, the locktime and threshold. These were already covered earlier in this step, so scroll back up if you require a refresher!



The next part is to create the mint output. This output can be used to create more asset tokens in the future. 



Then, we prepare a transaction that will create the asset based on the configurations set earlier. 



Now that we have our transaction, we will need to sign it using our keychain and issue it to the X-Chain. And we’re done!

So now you know what the code does, it is time to run the script to create your asset. You can do so by changing the value of the step variable on line 32 to 10. Following which, once you save the script, the script will be executed and your asset will be created. If everything is successful, your terminal output will display something similar to the image in ‘Expected output’.

With this you have created your asset on the X-Chain! Now you can copy the asset ID and paste it in line 29. The transaction ID will double as the asset ID. You can double check the asset creation using the Avalanche Wallet that we used earlier. Toggle back to the ‘Portfolio’ tab and click on the refresh button beside ‘Balance’, the page should show your newly created asset!

Do not worry if it only shows that the balance is 1. This is because the token had a denomination of 3 meaning that there will be 3 decimal places and since we only minted 1000 units, that would result in 1.000 being shown in the user interface.
Expected output
Step 11: Transferring Asset to Another Wallet
So now that you have created your new asset, let’s see how we can transfer our asset from the sender wallet to the recipient wallet. Same as before, we’ll be going through in detail what the code does. In particular, we’re referring to the sendAsset() function, which spans from line 141 to 182.


First, we would need to get the UTXO Set. As explained in the earlier step, UTXOs refer to unspent transactions. We will need to import the sender keypair into the keychain, then from there, we query the Testnet X-Chain to get its UTXO. 



Like before, we will need to craft the transaction so we will need to set the number of tokens to send and the asset ID. Here, we specify that we would like to set the quantity to be transferred to be 200 tokens. Note that your receiver address has already been set in the earlier steps. 



Once the transaction has been crafted, the transaction will be signed and issued on the X-Chain. 

At this point, if you have yet to replace the value of the assetID variable to your assetID, then do so at this point before proceeding. 

So now that you know what the code does, it is time to run the script to transfer your asset. You do so by switching the step variable on line 32 to 11. Following which, once you save the script, the script will be executed and your asset will be sent to the recipient address. If everything is successful, your terminal output will display something similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. 

If you were to access the Avalanche wallet again, you will see that you now only have 0.8 SU tokens. Awesome! Our script managed to send 200 of our SU tokens to our recipient account.
